ad", "label": "safe", "comment": "Removing link(s):Wikipedia:Articles for deletion/Eye Judahclosed as delete (XFDcloser)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_Ghanaian_musicians"}
{"title_page": "Maria Qamar", "text_new": "{{Use Canadian English|date=April 2020}}\n'''Maria Qamar''' (born c. 1990<ref name=\"nyt-2019\"/>)is an artist and author of the book ''Trust No Aunty.''<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.cbc.ca/books/why-maria-qamar-turned-her-art-into-a-guide-for-girls-growing-up-in-south-asian-families-1.4232133|title=Why Maria Qamar turned her art into a guide for girls growing up in South Asian families  {{!}} CBC Books|work=CBC|access-date=2018-05-23|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nQamar was born in [[Karachi]], [[Pakistan]] to a father from [[Bangladesh]] and a mother from [[Gujarat, India]].<ref name=\"bona\">{{cite news | title=Comic Relief | author-first=Priya | author-last=Krishna | magazine=Bon App\u00e9tit | date=August 2019 | page=42}}</ref> Both parents are [[chemist]]s.<ref name=\"tlife\"/> She was exposed to both [[Bengali culture]] and [[Gujarati culture]] growing up.<ref name=\"bona\"/>  \n\nIn 2000, when she was nine, the family emigrated to [[Ontario]], briefly residing in [[Scarborough, Toronto|Scarborough]].<ref name=\"tlife\">{{cite news | url=https://torontolife.com/style/fashion/torontos-stylish-maria-qamar/ | title=The Provocateur | author-first=  Katrina | author-last=Onstad | magazine=Toronto Life | date=April 9, 2018}}</ref>  The family then moved to [[Mississauga]], where she spent the rest of her childhood.<ref name=\"npr\">{{cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/2017/08/02/539598311/maria-qamar-dishes-up-desi-pop-in-trust-no-aunty|title=Maria Qamar Dishes Up Desi Pop in 'Trust No Aunty'|last=Lehoczy|first=Etelka|date=August 2, 2017|website=npr books}}</ref> She experienced prejudice and bullying against South Asian children in her school,<ref name=\"bona\"/> especially in the wake of the [[September 11, 2001 attacks]].<ref name=\"nyt-2019\"/> So as she later recalled, \"I started going home and drawing comics about these experiences. But I would change the outcome. In my comics I always got the last laugh.\"<ref name=\"bona\"/>  She aligned both with her [[Desi]] identity and with Western teen [[goth subculture|goth]], [[punk rock]], and [[heavy metal music|heavy metal]] subcultures.<ref name=\"tlife\"/><ref name=\"npr\"/>\n\nShe moved to Toronto and took a [[copywriting]] job in the [[advertising industry]].<ref name=\"tlife\"/>  This she did not like, and she was laid off around 2105.<ref name=\"tlife\"/><ref name=\"nyt-2019\"/> She then gained popularity as an artist through her [[Instagram]] page where she goes by the name of ''Hatecopy'' (the name indicating her feelings for her former field).<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thestar.com/entertainment/books/2017/08/01/they-gave-her-bad-advice-toronto-artist-maria-qamar-turned-it-into-a-book-trust-no-aunty.html|title=They gave her bad advice. Toronto artist Maria Qamar turned it into a book: \u2018Trust No Aunty\u2019|last=Lalani|first=Azzura|date=August 1, 2017|work=thestar.com}}</ref> As of 2019 she had a following of over 170,000 people on her Instagram platform.<ref name=\"nyt-2019\"/>\n\n{{Quote box | width=40% | align=right | quote=I realized that if you take a still from an Indian soap opera when it's zoomed in on somebody's face and you take a Roy Lichtenstein piece and you put them side by side, it's the exact same expression \u2014 but it's coming from two opposite ends of the planet. I decided to merge the two because it kind of described who I was as a person \u2014 I'm not one or the other. I don't have to choose. | author=Maria Qamar | source=<ref name=\"nyt-2019\"/> }}\n\nShe is known for her satirical lens commenting on the hybridization of South Asian and Canadian culture. She uses a pop art aesthetic to create works that tackle themes surrounding her experiences of racism, the first generation experience, body shaming, classism, and the patriarchy.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cbc.ca/arts/exhibitionists/pakistani-canadian-artist-maria-qamar-instagram-south-asian-pop-art-1.3488166|title=Pakistani-Canadian artist Maria Qamar's unique brand of pop art rules Instagram|last=Grundy|first=Mercedes|date=March 15, 2016|work=CBC}}</ref><ref name=\"Bascaramurty 2017\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/arts/books-and-media/canadian-artist-maria-qamar-calls-out-the-women-who-raised-her-in-new-book-trust-noaunty/article35868856/|title=Canadian artist Maria Qamar calls out the women who raised her in new book Trust No Aunty|last=Bascaramurty|first=Dakshana|date=August 2, 2017|work=The Globe and Mail|accessdate=March 11, 2018}}</ref> Her style is explicitly influenced by the work of [[Roy Lichtenstein]] and also by low culture such as [[Indian soap opera]]s; one of her first works was captioned \"what if Lichtenstein parodied Indian soap operas.\"<ref name=\"nyt-2019\"/>  She does not translate her works for Western audiences, instead leaving South Asian terms and themes in unaltered as she focuses on a Desi audience.<ref name=\"nyt-2019\"/><ref name=\"tlife\"/>\n\nQamar has sold work at exhibitions in Toronto, Los Angeles, New York and London. ''[[The Mindy Project]]'' creator and actor [[Mindy Kaling]] collects Qamar's work and her paintings decorated the set of that show.<ref name=\"Bascaramurty 2017\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://psmag.com/magazine/maria-qamar-guest-programmer|title=Artist Maria Qamar Blends South Asian Sensibilities With Pop Art|work=Pacific Standard|access-date=2018-05-23|language=en}}</ref>  She had also created murals, signs, and menu and plate designs for restaurants in various North American cities.<ref name=\"bona\"/>  \n\nA 2019 exhibition, entitled \"Fraaaandship!\", at the [[Richard Taittinger Gallery]] in New York brought her additional visibility as the youngest artist at the gallery and the first to come from an Instagram background.<ref name=\"nyt-2019\">{{cite news | title=Pop Art in South Asian Millennial Strokes | author-first=Alisha Haridasani | author-last=Gupta | newspaper=The New York Times | date=August 16, 2019 | page=C14}}</ref>\n\n''Trust no aunty'' won the 2018 [[Kobo Emerging Writer Prize]] for humour.<ref name=Cbc2018-06-19/>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|refs=\n<ref name=Cbc2018-06-19>\n{{cite news     \n| url         = https://www.cbc.ca/books/omar-el-akkad-author-of-american-war-among-winners-of-10k-kobo-emerging-writer-prizes-1.4712968\n| title       = Omar El Akkad, author of American War, among winners of $10K Kobo Emerging Writer Prizes\n| work        = [[CBC News]]\n| author      = Samraweet Yohannes\n| date        = 2018-06-19\n| accessdate  = 2019-06-11\n| url-status     = live \n}}\n</ref>\n}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Qamar, Maria}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Canadian women painters]]\n[[Category:21st-century Canadian painters]]\n[[Category:Pakistani emigrants to Canada]]\n[[Category:Naturalized citizens of Canada]]\n[[Category:People from Mississauga]]\n[[Category:People from Scarborough, Toronto]]\n[[Category:Artists from Toronto]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:21st-century Canadian women artists]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use Canadian English|date=April 2020}}\n'''Maria Qamar''' (born c. 1990<ref name=\"nyt-2019\"/>)is an artist and author of the book ''Trust No Aunty.''<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.cbc.ca/books/why-maria-qamar-turned-her-art-into-a-guide-for-girls-growing-up-in-south-asian-families-1.4232133|title=Why Maria Qamar turned her art into a guide for girls growing up in South Asian families  {{!}} CBC Books|work=CBC|access-date=2018-05-23|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nQamar was born in [[Karachi]], [[Pakistan]] to a father from [[Bangladesh]] and a mother from [[Gujarat, India]].<ref name=\"bona\">{{cite news | title=Comic Relief | author-first=Priya | author-last=Krishna | magazine=Bon App\u00e9tit | date=August 2019 | page=42}}</ref> Both parents are [[chemist]]s.<ref name=\"tlife\"/> She was exposed to both [[Bengali culture]] and [[Gujarati culture]] growing up.<ref name=\"bona\"/>  \n\nIn 2000, when she was nine, the family emigrated to [[Ontario]], briefly residing in [[Scarborough, Toronto|Scarborough]].<ref name=\"tlife\">{{cite news | url=https://torontolife.com/style/fashion/torontos-stylish-maria-qamar/ | title=The Provocateur | author-first=  Katrina | author-last=Onstad | magazine=Toronto Life | date=April 9, 2018}}</ref>  The family then moved to [[Mississauga]], where she spent the rest of her childhood.<ref name=\"npr\">{{cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/2017/08/02/539598311/maria-qamar-dishes-up-desi-pop-in-trust-no-aunty|title=Maria Qamar Dishes Up Desi Pop in 'Trust No Aunty'|last=Lehoczy|first=Etelka|date=August 2, 2017|website=npr books}}</ref> She experienced prejudice and bullying against South Asian children in her school,<ref name=\"bona\"/> especially in the wake of the [[September 11, 2001 attacks]].<ref name=\"nyt-2019\"/> So as she later recalled, \"I started going home and drawing comics about these experiences. But I would change the outcome. In my comics I always got the last laugh.\"<ref name=\"bona\"/>  She aligned both with her [[Desi]] identity and with Western teen [[goth]], [[punk rock]], and [[heavy metal]] subcultures.<ref name=\"tlife\"/><ref name=\"npr\"/>\n\nShe moved to Toronto and took a [[copywriting]] job in the [[advertising industry]].<ref name=\"tlife\"/>  This she did not like, and she was laid off around 2105.<ref name=\"tlife\"/><ref name=\"nyt-2019\"/> She then gained popularity as an artist through her [[Instagram]] page where she goes by the name of ''Hatecopy'' (the name indicating her feelings for her former field).<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thestar.com/entertainment/books/2017/08/01/they-gave-her-bad-advice-toronto-artist-maria-qamar-turned-it-into-a-book-trust-no-aunty.html|title=They gave her bad advice. Toronto artist Maria Qamar turned it into a book: \u2018Trust No Aunty\u2019|last=Lalani|first=Azzura|date=August 1, 2017|work=thestar.com}}</ref> As of 2019 she had a following of over 170,000 people on her Instagram platform.<ref name=\"nyt-2019\"/>\n\n{{Quote box | width=40% | align=right | quote=I realized that if you take a still from an Indian soap opera when it's zoomed in on somebody's face and you take a Roy Lichtenstein piece and you put them side by side, it's the exact same expression \u2014 but it's coming from two opposite ends of the planet. I decided to merge the two because it kind of described who I was as a person \u2014 I'm not one or the other. I don't have to choose. | author=Maria Qamar | source=<ref name=\"nyt-2019\"/> }}\n\nShe is known for her satirical lens commenting on the hybridization of South Asian and Canadian culture. She uses a pop art aesthetic to create works that tackle themes surrounding her experiences of racism, the first generation experience, body shaming, classism, and the patriarchy.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cbc.ca/arts/exhibitionists/pakistani-canadian-artist-maria-qamar-instagram-south-asian-pop-art-1.3488166|title=Pakistani-Canadian artist Maria Qamar's unique brand of pop art rules Instagram|last=Grundy|first=Mercedes|date=March 15, 2016|work=CBC}}</ref><ref name=\"Bascaramurty 2017\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/arts/books-and-media/canadian-artist-maria-qamar-calls-out-the-women-who-raised-her-in-new-book-trust-noaunty/article35868856/|title=Canadian artist Maria Qamar calls out the women who raised her in new book Trust No Aunty|last=Bascaramurty|first=Dakshana|date=August 2, 2017|work=The Globe and Mail|accessdate=March 11, 2018}}</ref> Her style is explicitly influenced by the work of [[Roy Lichtenstein]] and also by low culture such as [[Indian soap opera]]s; one of her first works was captioned \"what if Lichtenstein parodied Indian soap operas.\"<ref name=\"nyt-2019\"/>  She does not translate her works for Western audiences, instead leaving South Asian terms and themes in unaltered as she focuses on a Desi audience.<ref name=\"nyt-2019\"/><ref name=\"tlife\"/>\n\nQamar has sold work at exhibitions in Toronto, Los Angeles, New York and London. ''[[The Mindy Project]]'' creator and actor [[Mindy Kaling]] collects Qamar's work and her paintings decorated the set of that show.<ref name=\"Bascaramurty 2017\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://psmag.com/magazine/maria-qamar-guest-programmer|title=Artist Maria Qamar Blends South Asian Sensibilities With Pop Art|work=Pacific Standard|access-date=2018-05-23|language=en}}</ref>  She had also created murals, signs, and menu and plate designs for restaurants in various North American cities.<ref name=\"bona\"/>  \n\nA 2019 exhibition, entitled \"Fraaaandship!\", at the [[Richard Taittinger Gallery]] in New York brought her additional visibility as the youngest artist at the gallery and the first to come from an Instagram background.<ref name=\"nyt-2019\">{{cite news | title=Pop Art in South Asian Millennial Strokes | author-first=Alisha Haridasani | author-last=Gupta | newspaper=The New York Times | date=August 16, 2019 | page=C14}}</ref>\n\n''Trust no aunty'' won the 2018 [[Kobo Emerging Writer Prize]] for humour.<ref name=Cbc2018-06-19/>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|refs=\n<ref name=Cbc2018-06-19>\n{{cite news     \n| url         = https://www.cbc.ca/books/omar-el-akkad-author-of-american-war-among-winners-of-10k-kobo-emerging-writer-prizes-1.4712968\n| title       = Omar El Akkad, author of American War, among winners of $10K Kobo Emerging Writer Prizes\n| work        = [[CBC News]]\n| author      = Samraweet Yohannes\n| date        = 2018-06-19\n| accessdate  = 2019-06-11\n| url-status     = live \n}}\n</ref>\n}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Qamar, Maria}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Canadian women painters]]\n[[Category:21st-century Canadian painters]]\n[[Category:Pakistani emigrants to Canada]]\n[[Category:Naturalized citizens of Canada]]\n[[Category:People from Mississauga]]\n[[Category:People from Scarborough, Toronto]]\n[[Category:Artists from Toronto]]\n[[Category:Year